==English==

===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|spang||a small piece of ornamental metal; spangle; small ornament; a bowl or cup|lang=enm}}, likely from {{etyl|dum|en}} {{term|spange||buckle, clasp|lang=dum}} or {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|spang||buckle, clasp|lang=ang}}

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# {{obsolete}} A shiny [[ornament]] or object; a [[spangle]]
#* Spenser
#*: With glittering '''spangs''' that did like stars appear.

====Verb====
{{en-verb}}

# To set with bright points: star or spangle.
# To [[hitch]]; [[fasten]].

===Etymology 2===
Onomatopoeia

====Verb====
{{en-verb}}

# {{intransitive|of a flying object such as a bullet}} To strike or ricochet with a loud report
#* '''1895''', {{w|Stephen Crane}}, ''{{w|The Red Badge of Courage}}''
#*: Occasional bullets buzzed in the air and '''spanged''' into tree trunks.
#* '''1918''', {{w|Zane Grey}}, ''The U.P. Trail''
#*: How clear, sweet, '''spanging''' the hammer blows!

